as it chains multiple agentic steps together.\n\nFor probability distributions, I'm assessing confidence in each level. The function signature matching the interface requires a real LLM call to catch actual failures, making Agentic dominant at 0.85, with minimal probability at Unit (0.0) and small chances at Integration, System, and Workflow (0.05 each).\n\nReconsidering the first behavior: even with a mock LLM, I could test signature parsing logic at Integration level, but the core failure—LLM generating an incorrect signature—demands an actual agentic test. Adjusting the distribution: Unit stays at 0.0, while Integration, System, and Workflow each get 0.02, leaving Agentic at 0.94. The sum checks out at 1.0.\n\nFor the second behavior, generated code passing test cases requires real execution and an actual LLM, making Agentic dominant at 0.8. System testing contributes 0.1 since it involves real code execution, Integration adds 0.05 with mocked execution, and Workflow rounds out the remaining 0.05. Unit testing can't validate code execution at all.\n\nThe third behavior—failure messages being incorporated into refinement—can't be verified without integration, so Unit remains at 0.0. Integration testing begins to capture this with mocked execution, though the LLM's ability to use feedback effectively is the primary variable. The core mechanism here is whether failure messages actually get captured and included in the next prompt—that's testable at Integration level by generating failing code, verifying the error messages are captured, and checking they appear in the subsequent LLM input. However, the practical value of the behavior—whether the LLM actually understands those messages and produces better code—requires real LLM calls across multiple cycles, pushing into Agentic or Workflow territory. Real failures could manifest as messages not being captured at all, formatting issues, or omission from the prompt (all Integration-catchable), versus the LLM failing to comprehend or act on the feedback (Agentic/Workflow-level). The mechanism itself is the primary concern, so Integration at 0.65 seems appropriate for catching the core failure mode.\n\nFor behavior 4, the critical aspect is control flow—stopping after exactly 3 attempts and returning an error. This requires coordinating multiple components (attempt counter, LLM calls, error handling), making it fundamentally an Integration test at 0.75. I can mock the LLM and verify the loop terminates correctly. System and Agentic testing could happen with real code or real LLM calls, but the behavior being tested is the control logic itself, not the quality of outputs.\n\nBehavior 5 is different—a full loop producing working code depends entirely on LLM quality across multiple iterations. Integration testing with mocks can't verify this since mocks won't generate real implementations. This is primarily a Workflow test at 0.75, where multiple agentic steps execute in sequence and the final output is actually functional code. Agentic testing at 0.2 covers single-loop iterations, while System testing at 0.05 could run real code but doesn't capture the multi-step refinement cycle.\n\nFor test descriptions: signature matching requires calling a real LLM, extracting the generated signature, and verifying parameter names, types, and return type align with the specification. Code generation and execution involves calling the real LLM to produce code, running it against a test suite, and confirming all tests pass or iterating until they do. Failure message inclusion means generating intentionally failing code, capturing the failure output, passing that context back to the LLM in the prompt, and verifying the refined code incorporates the failure details. The stop-after-3-attempts test uses a mocked LLM that always fails, verifying exactly 3 refinement iterations occur before returning a structured error with all attempts and results. The full-loop test provides a genuinely difficult function description, runs the complete refinement cycle with a real LLM and real test suite, and confirms the final output passes all tests after multiple iterations.\n\nFor plan_consistent verification, I need to determine whether each test actually matches the level I assigned. Test 3 is the tricky one—if I'm mocking the LLM to fail predictably and just verifying failure messages are captured and included in the mock's input, that's Integration level. But if I'm testing whether failure messages actually help the real LLM improve its output, that's Agentic. I should clarify my test descriptions to be explicit about whether they use real or mocked LLMs, since that distinction determines the appropriate level. The test description should clarify that we're mocking the LLM and inspecting its call arguments to verify the prompt includes failure messages.\n\nFor stopping after max attempts, I'd mock both the LLM (to always return failing code) and test execution, then run the service and confirm it makes exactly 3 attempts before returning a structured error containing all attempts and their results. This is an Integration test.\n\nThe full loop test uses a real LLM and real test suite with a function description that typically requires multiple refinement cycles. Running the service with refinement enabled (up to 3 attempts) should produce code that passes all tests—this is a Workflow test since it chains multiple agentic steps together.\n\nChecking plan_consistent: test 1 is Agentic (real LLM), test 2 is Agentic plus System code execution, and test 3 is Integration. Tests 4 and 5 are Integration and Workflow respectively.\n\nFor behavior 2, I need to determine whether Agentic or System is the minimum level. Both the LLM non-determinism and real code execution are required. The LLM's quality is the limiting factor—I could theoretically mock code execution but not the LLM's output, so Agentic is the minimum infrastructure needed.\n\nThe realistic failure modes are syntax errors in generated code, logic errors, or test failures. Catching all of these requires both System-level code execution and Agentic-level LLM quality. The core of behavior 2 is whether the generated implementation passes tests, which depends on both the LLM generating code and that code actually executing and being tested.\n\nSince both capabilities are essential, neither System nor Agentic alone is sufficient. System-level testing handles code execution through subprocess calls, while Agentic-level testing captures LLM non-determinism. The minimum viable test level needs to account for both the unpredictability of the LLM and the actual execution of the code it produces.\n\nThe key question is what failure mode you're actually trying to catch. If it's poor code generation from the LLM, that points to Agentic level. If it's execution failures, that's System level. For this behavior, the primary risk is LLM quality—the code execution serves mainly as verification. Using the MOCK-MISS framework: you could mock both the LLM (returning valid code) and the execution environment (returning success), but this wouldn't catch the real failure where the LLM generates problematic code. This suggests you need to move beyond mocking to real LLM calls and actual execution.\n\nThe practical minimum is Agentic level because most failure risk concentrates in LLM output quality, while code execution is relatively reliable. Since Agentic level includes subprocess capabilities, you can perform real code testing there. The test ultimately requires both a genuine LLM call and actual code execution to be meaningful.\n\nFor Behavior 2, the limiting constraint is LLM non-determinism. Unit testing can't capture this at all. Integration testing might mock both the LLM and tests but would miss real failures. System level handles code execution but doesn't address LLM quality issues. Agentic level covers both real LLM calls and code execution, making it the only viable option. Workflow level doesn't apply since this isn't a multi-step process.\n\nFor Behavior 3, I need to verify that failure messages actually feed into subsequent LLM prompts. The approach would be to create code designed to fail, run the service, and observe whether those failures appear in the next prompt.\n\nThe challenge is that mocking the LLM before the first call lets me control what bad code it generates, ensuring I have a failure to work with. Without mocking, the real LLM might return working code immediately, leaving nothing to refine. So I'd mock the LLM to return specific broken code initially, run the actual tests to capture real failures, then verify those failures show up in the next LLM call by inspecting the prompt arguments.\n\nThe core mechanism—ensuring failure messages get passed to the LLM—lives at the Integration level. But truly validating that the refinement produces better code requires the Agentic level, where the LLM actually improves its output. For behavior 3, I'm setting Integration at 0.7 since that's where the message-passing mechanism gets verified, with Agentic at 0.2 for improvement validation, and small weights on System and Workflow for edge cases.\n\nNow I need to reconsider behavior 1 more carefully. The function signature matching could fail in two distinct ways: the LLM might generate incorrect parameter names or types (Agentic-level failure), or my parsing logic might extract the wrong signature from correct LLM output (Integration-level failure). Integration tests can mock the LLM and verify the parsing works correctly, but catching actual generation errors requires a real LLM call. Comprehensive coverage means testing both the parsing robustness and the LLM's ability to generate proper signatures.\n\nThe most probable failure point is the LLM itself rather than the parsing logic, so Agentic testing is the minimum level needed to catch real failures. I should structure the test descriptions to be implementable and explain both what's being tested and why that test level is necessary.\n\nFor the signature matching test, I'd call the real LLM with a function description, parse the output, and verify parameter names, types, and return type align with the specification. The implementation test would generate code from a description and execute it against the provided test suite to ensure all tests pass. For failure message handling, I'd mock the LLM's initial response to fail tests, then verify the refinement prompt includes those failure messages as context. Finally, I'd mock the LLM to always return failing code and confirm the service stops after exactly 3 generation attempts.\n\nThe full integration test would use a genuinely difficult function description where single LLM calls typically struggle, running the complete service with real LLM and test suite to confirm iterative refinement produces passing code within the attempt limit.\n\nFor the justifications: Generated code quality fundamentally depends on the LLM's reasoning ability—mocks can't expose these gaps, so both real LLM calls and actual test execution are necessary to catch logic errors. Error message capture and formatting into subsequent prompts can be verified at the integration level by mocking LLM responses and inspecting the prompt arguments passed to the next call. The retry loop's control flow—stopping conditions, error aggregation, response structure—is testable with mocked LLM and test execution since the focus is on orchestration logic rather than LLM quality. Finally, validating that the full workflow actually solves difficult problems requires real LLM calls where each refinement builds on previous test failures.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the probability assignments for each level. For signature matching, real LLM is essential since I need to verify the model can actually generate correct signatures—mocking can't validate this capability. Unit testing alone is insufficient, and integration testing with mocks wouldn't catch whether the LLM produces valid signatures. So Agentic should have very high probability.\n\nFor implementation passing tests, the real constraint is LLM quality, not just code execution. Integration testing with mocks misses actual model failures, while system-level testing provides code execution but still depends on the LLM's actual performance. Agentic testing with a real model is where the real validation happens.\n\nFor failure messages in refinement, I can verify the mechanism at integration level by checking that the system detects and reports failures, but Agentic testing would confirm the LLM actually improves its output through refinement cycles.\n\nControl flow for the retry limit works at integration level—I can mock the LLM and verify the system stops after three attempts without needing full agentic validation.\n\nThe complete loop solving a difficult problem requires workflow-level testing since it involves multiple sequential agentic cycles that can't be validated through mocks alone.\n\nAll five scenarios sum to 1.0 across test levels. Now I need to assess plan_consistent similarly.\n\nEach test description aligns with its chosen level: agentic tests with real LLM calls, integration tests with mocked components, and the workflow test spanning multiple steps with a real LLM. Everything checks out. Time to format the structured output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12632,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12632},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"76aafc34-b125-4527-9dee-866adb2a1be9","uuid":"7f96c7c8-c8f5-4349-b7d8-478828beea7a"}
